Recommendations
The Netherlands has set itself a target of becoming 50% circular by 2030 and 100% by 2050, but most governments have yet to wake up to the potential of the circular economy. The report calls on governments to ensure that climate change and circular economy strategies are joined up to achieve maximum impact, using tax and spending plans to drive change. They should:
· Abolish financial incentives which encourage overuse of natural resources, such as subsidies for fossil fuel exploration, extraction and consumption;
· Raise taxes on emissions, excessive resource extraction and waste production, for example by implementing a gradually increasing carbon tax;
· Lower taxes on labour, knowledge and innovation and invest in these areas.

The report calls on governments to ensure that climate change and circular economy strategies are joined up to achieve maximum impact, using tax and spending plans to drive change. They should:
· Abolish financial incentives which encourage overuse of natural resources, such as subsidies for fossil fuel exploration, extraction and consumption;
· Raise taxes on emissions, excessive resource extraction and waste production, for example by implementing a gradually increasing carbon tax;
· Lower taxes on labour, knowledge and innovation and invest in these areas. Lower labour taxes will encourage labour-intensive parts of a circular economy such as take-back schemes and recycling.

